english:
  title: Epitaph for the Tomb of Min Gong, posthumously titled Munon, Minister of Advanced Rectitude
  author: Lee Dal-chung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my youth, I studied under the Great Man and heard him speak. Whenever he discussed the way of scholars, he would sigh deeply and lament: "The present age is not what the past was." I thought his words too severe and wondered why he spoke thus. Yet after many years of witnessing the world's affairs, I came to believe his words were true. The refined spirit of our elders fades day by day, leaving us desolate with no model to follow. Thus longing for the ancients rises unbidden—how can one not grieve?

    I have been bound to the Minister by kinship and affection. When he passed, my sorrow ran deep. His widow twice requested I compose his epitaph. How could I refuse, though my brush is clumsy?

    The Minister's name was Sipyeong, his courtesy name Tanbu, and his pen name Gupam. He was from Yeohung in Chungju. His father bore the rank of Eminent Rectifier and held the highest offices, with the posthumous name Munshun. His mother, of the Kim clan, was the daughter of a great general and was enfeoffed as Lady of Yonggap. His grandfather was enfeoffed with great honors, bearing the posthumous name Chunshun. His family had sown virtue for generations—nine generations back, his ancestor Seongdo served as imperial attendant, and from thence forth, each generation produced great ministers. Their accomplishments and ranks stretch in an unbroken line, recorded in family records and national histories.

    The Minister was born in the twelfth month of a propitious year. Orphaned at five, he was raised by his grandfather and proved to possess exceptional talent and bearing. The great Minister Kim, renowned as a judge of character, gave him his daughter in marriage. Through this connection to an esteemed household and observing the luminaries who gathered there, the Minister's learning advanced daily.

    He first served as an inspector of imperial stores, then rose through military ranks, though he devoted himself more to study than to office. When the great examination was held, the examining official, a man of exacting standards, admitted fewer than the usual quota, taking only those of true merit. The Minister was among the successful. Thus he spent ten years mastering scholarship.

    When a former ruler returned to power, the Minister was appointed to edit both the Records and Spring and Autumn Annals, then served as advisor and censor, receiving official robes of silver and purple. When a new ruler ascended who favored warriors over scholars, the Minister, serving as a military clerk and court official, maintained his integrity without wavering.

    When another ruler restored order, the Minister was appointed to high offices of ceremony and record-keeping, then sent out to govern Gyeongsang Province with such skill that the people thrived. Recalled to the capital, he became Dean of the National Academy and editor of the Spring and Autumn Annals. He rose through ranks of increasing honor until he served as Inspector of Jeolla Province, where he governed with such grace and virtue that all prospered.

    Returning to the capital, he became Great Dean of the Academy and was entrusted with selecting candidates in the great examinations, choosing ninety-three scholars of genuine merit. When a new regime took power, he was appointed to high ministerial rank, though he later chose to withdraw and live in quiet retirement for eight years.

    At sixty-five, in the seventh month of an auspicious year, he passed away at his home. When word reached the throne, the ruler mourned deeply and bestowed upon him the posthumous title of Munon, the Warm and Cultured.

    Consider the Minister's life: from an illustrious family with generations of high service, yet he never showed pride. His nature was warm and refined. With kinsmen and relations, he was gracious and harmonious. Even when displeased, he said nothing, allowing others to recognize their fault and submit. He loved good company and especially admired the writings of Scholar Choe, spending his own fortune to print them. His faithfulness to virtue and generosity knew no bounds.

    In office, he was neither rigid nor eccentric, but followed righteousness alone. He delighted in poetry and wine, maintaining an open and honest heart—a true exemplar of the noble person. Looking upon such a man, one cannot say that the scholar's spirit has entirely declined from antiquity. And yet—he is gone, and all I observe now is novelty and change. Thus I find myself sighing without knowing why: "The present age is indeed not what the past was." So have I come to believe the wisdom of the Great Man's words.

    The Minister fathered one daughter, whom he married to a gentleman of good family. He had two grandsons, whom he cherished and educated well—both passed the examinations with distinction. He had four granddaughters, the eldest married to a man of noble house, the others still young. His grandsons conducted his funeral rites with perfect propriety, and he was laid to rest on an auspicious day at a serene monastery site.

    His epitaph reads:

    As generous as the Minister, as pure as the Minister—
    this is what people admire.
    Yet why did heaven grant him no son to carry on?
    Heaven's ways are hard to trust.

    He left behind a virtuous daughter and a worthy son-in-law—
    this alone consoles my heart.

    His poetry held subtle depths, his prose achieved noble heights,
    allowing me to ponder them long:

    Centered without leaning, unified without faction,
    sincere in all things—
    thus he lived.

    When I recall him, he seems still present,
    yet alas, he cannot be seen again.

    How swiftly the years fly by!

    Oh, that such a man should depart this world.
  footnotes:
    - The full title of the Minister reflects his many offices and honors throughout a long career spanning several reigns and dynastic transitions.
    - The Minister lived during the Yuan dynasty's rule over Korea, a period of significant political complexity and foreign influence.
    - His family's service spanning nine generations represents exceptional continuity in Korea's aristocratic scholar-official class.
    - The reference to 'Great Man' (대인) in the opening and closing frames the entire epitaph as both personal reflection and philosophical meditation on virtue and history.
